    q: "Is fresh-roasted coffee better for espresso?",
    a: "Yes, but there is a nuance: very freshly roasted coffee (within 1-5 days of roasting) is often too gassy for consistent espresso extraction. CO2 released during extraction causes channeling and uneven shots. Most specialty roasters and baristas recommend resting espresso beans 7 to 14 days post-roast before brewing. After that rest, fresh-roasted beans in the 7-21 day post-roast window are significantly better for espresso than stale coffee. The roast date on the bag is the tool for managing this. Without a roast date, you cannot time your rest period."
  },
  {
    q: "Should I rest beans before extracting espresso?",
    a: "Yes. Resting allows CO2 to off-gas from the bean, which stabilizes extraction and produces more consistent shots. The recommended rest period for espresso is 7 to 14 days post-roast for medium to medium-dark roasts; lighter roasts may need up to 3 weeks to fully off-gas and open up. If your shots are producing large bubbles at the surface (excessive crema) and tasting sour or uneven despite correct parameters, under-rested beans are the likely cause. Conversely, coffee rested longer than 4 weeks past roast is stale."
  },
  {
    q: "What grind size should I use for espresso?",
    a: "Espresso grind is the finest practical grind setting for a burr grinder, producing a fine powder that resembles table salt or slightly finer. The exact setting varies by grinder. A correctly ground espresso dose at 18g should extract in 25-30 seconds under 9 bars of pressure at a 1:2 dose-to-yield ratio (18g in, 36g out). If your shot pulls faster than 25 seconds, grind finer. If slower than 30 seconds, grind coarser. Adjust in small increments: espresso is sensitive to even minor grind changes."
  },
  {
    q: "Does expensive coffee make better espresso?",
    a: "Not automatically, and in some cases expensive light-roasted single-origins are harder to extract well for espresso than a well-designed medium-roast blend at half the price. Espresso is a pressure-brewing method that rewards sweetness, body, and structural balance over the delicate floral or citrus aromatics that make a pour-over exceptional. A $25/lb blend designed for espresso will often outperform a $45/lb light-roasted Ethiopian single-origin in an espresso machine unless you have the equipment and skill to dial in the single-origin precisely. For most home espresso setups, a purpose-roasted espresso blend is the pragmatic choice."
  },
