    q: "Can you use single-origin coffee for espresso?",
    a: "Yes, and it can be transcendent when done well. Single-origin espresso rewards precision: the narrower flavor profile of a single origin concentrated under 9 bars of pressure is more sensitive to extraction variables than a blend designed to smooth out inconsistencies. High-acid single-origins (Kenyan, Ethiopian washed) can taste sour at standard espresso temperatures and may need lower temperature extraction or higher dose ratios. Medium-bodied, naturally sweet origins (Colombian, Brazilian, Guatemalan) integrate more easily into espresso parameters. If you want to try single-origin espresso, start with a Colombian or Brazilian single-origin before attempting a high-acid African origin."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the ideal extraction ratio for espresso?",
    a: "The standard specialty espresso ratio is 1:2 (dose to yield by weight). At 18g of ground coffee in, target 36g of liquid espresso out, extracted in 25-30 seconds at 9 bars and 90-96°C. Ristretto pulls use a tighter 1:1.5 ratio for a sweeter, more concentrated shot. Lungo pulls use a wider 1:3 or 1:4 ratio for a more dilute, bitter-leaning shot. Most specialty coffee is best at the standard 1:2 ratio. Adjust by taste: if the shot is bitter, try a slightly wider ratio or coarser grind. If sour, tighter ratio or finer grind."
