<h2 class="section-head">What Makes a Coffee <em>Work for Espresso</em></h2>

<p class="body"><strong>Body.</strong> Espresso needs body. Body is the textural weight and mouthfeel of the cup, and at espresso concentration it determines whether the shot feels rich and coating or thin and hollow. Coffees with naturally higher body come from lower-altitude origins, natural process methods, and varietals with higher lipid content. Brazilian natural and Colombian medium-roast are reliable body sources. Very light-roasted high-altitude single-origins often lack the body for satisfying espresso unless blended with something heavier.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Sweetness.</strong> Sweetness in espresso comes from the natural sugars developed during cherry ripening and concentrated by the roasting process. Without sweetness, espresso is bitter. Sweetness is why medium-roasted coffee is the specialty sweet spot for espresso: light roasts have not developed the sugars fully; dark roasts have burned through them into bitter caramelization and char. Naturally sweet origins (Colombia, Guatemala, some Brazilians) hit this balance more easily than high-acid African origins.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Acidity.</strong> Medium acidity integrates well into espresso; high acidity produces sour shots. Ethiopian washed coffees and Kenyan coffees, beloved for their bright acidity in pour-over, can taste uncomfortably sour in espresso if not dialed in precisely at lower extraction temperatures. Medium-acid origins (Colombia, Guatemala, Honduras) are more forgiving at standard espresso parameters (92-94°C). This does not mean high-acid coffees cannot work as espresso, but they require more precision to extract well.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Roast level.</strong> Medium is the sweet spot for most espresso. Light roast coffee is denser (harder to extract evenly), retains more acidity (risks sour shots), and requires more precise dialing in than medium-roasted coffee. Dark roast coffee has the body and lower acidity that makes extraction consistent, but darker roasting masks origin character behind roast flavors (dark chocolate, char, tobacco) that make one dark-roasted espresso blend indistinguishable from another. Medium roast preserves origin sweetness and character while providing enough structural development for consistent extraction.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Single-Origin Espresso vs. Blends: <em>An Honest Assessment</em></h2>

<p class="body">Blends are designed for espresso, and they are good at it. A well-constructed espresso blend layers origins for complementary reasons: Brazilian natural for body and chocolate, Colombian for sweetness and balance, a touch of Ethiopian for brightness. The blend is deliberately engineered to hit consistent extraction parameters across roast batches. It is more forgiving to pull, more consistent shot to shot, and requires less precision to dial in. For cafés serving high volume, blends make practical and quality sense.</p>

<p class="body">Single-origin espresso is riskier and more demanding. The narrower flavor profile concentrates under pressure in a way that either reveals something exceptional or reveals every flaw in the bean, the roast, or the extraction. When it works, a single-origin espresso shot from a Nyeri cooperative's SL-28 or a Nariño high-altitude Caturra is something a blend cannot replicate: a specific, identifiable place expressed through espresso. When it does not work, it is sour, one-dimensional, or empty.</p>

<p class="body">The honest guide: if you have a home espresso setup that lets you control variables (temperature, dose, grind, yield, time), single-origin espresso is worth exploring once you have the fundamentals dialed. If you are still working on consistent shots, a purpose-roasted espresso blend is more efficient to learn on and produces better results more reliably.</p>

