<h2 class="section-head">Dialing In: <em>A Practical Guide</em></h2>

<p class="body">The variables for espresso extraction interact with each other. Adjusting one changes the outcome of the others. Here is the sequence:</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Dose.</strong> Start at 18g of ground coffee for a standard double shot in a 58mm portafilter. This is the most widely used starting point for specialty espresso. Adjust by 0.5g increments if you find your grinder cannot hit the extraction window at 18g.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Grind.</strong> Grind size is the primary extraction control. Finer grind slows water flow, extends extraction time, increases yield per shot, and tends toward bitterness. Coarser grind speeds water flow, shortens extraction time, decreases yield, and tends toward sourness. When dialing in a new coffee, start with what you know and adjust grind until your shot hits 25-30 seconds to 36g out. Make one grind adjustment at a time: the grind dial is sensitive.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Yield.</strong> At 18g in, target 36g out for a standard 1:2 espresso. Weigh your yield with a scale. Guessing by volume is imprecise because crema volume varies by coffee freshness, roast level, and extraction. A scale removes that variable.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Time.</strong> 25 to 30 seconds from the first drop of espresso to reaching your target yield. If you are within that window at your target dose and yield, you have a correctly extracted shot. If the shot is still not tasting right, the problem is more likely the coffee, the water, or the machine temperature than the parameters.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Light vs. Dark Roast for Espresso: <em>The Real Tradeoff</em></h2>

<p class="body"><strong>Light roast espresso</strong> is harder to dial in. The dense bean structure resists extraction and requires finer grind, higher temperature, or longer extraction time relative to medium roast. The acidity retained from light roasting can read as sourness if under-extracted. When dialed in correctly, light-roasted single-origin espresso can be extraordinary: a floral, fruit-forward shot with complexity that blends cannot achieve. The reward is real; so is the demand for precision.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Medium roast</strong> is the specialty sweet spot for most espresso applications. Sugar development is optimized, body is adequate, acidity is integrated rather than sharp, and the extraction window is wide enough to hit consistently without dialing in to the fraction. Coffee Bros. espresso and Koa Coffee are both at this level.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Dark roast</strong> espresso has the most body and the lowest acidity, making it the easiest to extract consistently. The tradeoff is that dark roasting masks origin character behind roast flavors: dark chocolate, char, bitterness, tobacco. A well-extracted dark-roast espresso is satisfying in a classic way, but it tastes of roasting technique rather than origin. Five Star's medium-dark lands at the edge of this range while preserving enough sweetness to distinguish it from commodity dark-roast blends.</p>

